label chapter4:

    # [Scene: Town Square | Morning]

    scene bg ch4_453e40_1 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, ascending strings with light percussion]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low murmur of the crowd, a distant axle creaking as a cart stops, the occasional gull call]
    "You stand behind the podium, satchel at your feet, the sea-glass pendant cool against your collarbone. The prints and sketches you smoothed into folders feel like small islands of certainty in a tide of questions. You"
    "remember the lighthouse lamp pulsing amber, the hush that met your breath last time — and you remember choosing a path: the hybrid plan, Elliot's plan, the one that reaches for both marsh and market."
    "Your voice forms around the plan like a rope thrown across water: meant to connect, steady enough to be held."
    show maya_ibarra at left:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "Good morning. Thank you for coming."
    "The applause is modest, earnest. Rosa stands off to your left, camera at eye level, catching faces — wrinkled, sunburned, skeptical, hopeful. You let your eyes sweep the crowd until they find familiar anchors: Mayor Cortez's"
    "steady profile, Tomas's slow, approving nod, a cluster of fishermen with salt in their hair."
    "You pull the first sheet from the folder. The sketches are Elliot Chen's: clean lines, hand-annotated marsh elevations, places where woven coir rolls nestle with planted reeds. You could smell a faint oil of pasted inks and the dampness of printed paper."
    "You inhale again."

    maya_ibarra "Port Veridian doesn't need a quick fix. We need something that withstands storms and rebuilds what the water has taken. Elliot and I have been working on a pilot — a living dike that blends engineered supports with marsh restoration. It will protect the shoreline and help the ecosystem recover, while creating local jobs to build and maintain it."
    "Elliot Chen steps forward beside you. His trench coat still bears a fine trace of estuary mud on the hem; he unfolds his roll-up sketch cloth like a map of a hopeful coast. When he catches"
    "your eye you see the way his storm-blue gaze softens — not just for the plan, but for you."
    show elliot_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "We'll start small, right here at the estuary. Coir rolls, native reeds, braided rope anchors. Sensors will tell us how it performs. The goal is to learn fast and adapt faster."
    "Crowd voices rise. A fisherman — older, skeptical — folds his arms."

    "Fisherman" "Learning won't keep nets full if the next storm takes the season."
    "You hear Noah Rhee's voice cut through, low and carried by the wind. He stands a little apart, jaw set, eyes fixed on the sketches as though measuring them against the horizon."
    show noah_rhee at center:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_rhee "This is fine in a calm year. If the surge comes, we need to know who’s fixing our boats in the morning."
    "You feel the tension tighten like a line around your chest. People need both reassurance and results. You reach for honesty as much as you reach for rhetoric."

    maya_ibarra "You're right. We need both: immediate protections and long-term resilience. That's why this pilot is built to be rapidly deployable and repairable by local crews. It won't be a replacement for emergency work — it'll be part of the same system. We can teach, employ, and protect at the same time."

    "Mayor Cortez" "If the pilot demonstrates clear metrics and community oversight, I will push for expedited permits and municipal support."
    "A ripple of relief passes through the crowd. In the back, Rosa gives you a tiny thumbs-up before focusing her lens again."

    menu:
        "Open with technical detail to reassure engineers":
            "You lean into the schematics, pointing to the sensor nodes and load-bearing braided anchors; murmurs of technical approval spread."
        "Tell a personal story about your father to connect emotionally":
            "You tell of a night with wind like teeth and a father's hands that wouldn't let the dock go; a hush falls, faces soften, and someone in the front row reaches out to steady a child."

    # --- merge ---
    "Elliot Chen moves to your right, unrolling the finer details. He speaks with a steady cadence that makes complex things feel approachable."

    elliot_chen "Dr. Kira's team has already modeled sediment accretion rates. The sensors will give us salinity, wave force, and soil compaction data in real time. We'll publish everything openly — everyone can see what's working and what's not."
    "Dr. Kira Ansel steps forward from the Tidewatch Lab contingent, wiping her hands on a field vest as if to erase hours of work and hand over what remains: clarity."
    hide maya_ibarra
    show dr_kira_ansel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kira_ansel "I want to be clear — the sensors won't replace local knowledge. They augment it. We'll train volunteer techs, and we'll have redundant data links to prevent blind spots."
    "Noah Rhee watches, jaw tense. When you finish, he approaches, not with the open hand you sometimes expect, but with a small coil of rope thrown over his shoulder like an offering in a language you both understand."

    noah_rhee "I came down early. If you're going to do this, you need people who know how a tide really moves. I don't agree with everything, but if you're asking for hands, I'm giving mine."
    "The way he says it is distant, but the rope he sets on the ground is real, heavy with salt and braided from years of use. You accept it with both gratitude and the ache of all the things unsaid between you."
    hide elliot_chen
    show maya_ibarra at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "Thank you. We'll need your crews on the anchors and the heavy lifting."
    "Noah Rhee grunts, then walks off to organize a small group. He doesn't look at you when he leaves; the gesture is its own reconciliation."
    # [Scene: Estuary / Living Dike Pilot Site | Midday]
    hide noah_rhee
    hide dr_kira_ansel
    hide maya_ibarra

    scene bg ch4_453e40_2 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Light percussion, choral warmth underneath]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Rope rasping, laughter, the slap of water against coir, birds in the reeds]
    "You are no longer at the podium. You are elbow-deep in the making of something. Volunteers — teenagers, retirees, fishermen, your sister Rosa with her camera slung to her side — bend and braid, tamp and"
    "stake. The smell of wet coir and mud mixes with the salty air; your gloves squeak as they rub against braided rope."
    "You delegate. It is small miracles of trust: someone to roll the coir, someone to plant, someone to drive piles. For the first time in months, you feel the relief of not doing everything yourself."
    "You can let go without abandoning the outcome. Delegation is not lesser duty — it's the way this gets built."
    "Elliot Chen stays close, advising where to place a sensor mast, his fingers ink-smudged and sure. He brushes mud off your sleeve with the back of his hand; the touch is mundane and intimate."
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "You made me put extra anchors near that shoal. You told me to be stubborn."
    show maya_ibarra at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "Someone had to. I don't trust elegant designs without stubborn anchors."
    "His laugh softens, and for a heartbeat there is only the rhythm of work and the small, steadying nearness between you. You trade tips — how to thread a coir roll so it won't unravel under pressure, how to plant reeds to maximize root spread."
    "Rosa crouches at your feet, camera clicking."
    show rosa_ibarra at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_ibarra "This is exactly the kind of thing that shows in a single frame. People making a future with their hands."
    "She shoots photos of calloused hands, of Elliot Chen squinting in the light, of Noah Rhee teaching a group of young fishermen to tie a complicated knot. In one sequence, Noah Rhee's concentration loosens into a brief smile when a kid gets it right."
    hide elliot_chen
    show noah_rhee at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_rhee "That kid's quicker than most of my crew were at that age."

    maya_ibarra "He'll keep the knot when the tide pulls. He learns faster than some adults."
    "Noah Rhee inclines his head in the smallest concession; the distance between you feels narrower."

    menu:
        "Invite Noah to lead the anchoring team publicly":
            "You call out Noah by name and hand him the lead rope. He stiffens, then accepts with a short nod; the crowd acknowledges him with a hesitant round of approval."
        "Keep the leadership distributed to avoid spotlight":
            "You hand out tasks evenly, letting accomplishment speak. Noah takes a corner without fanfare, and his work becomes visible in quiet, steady results."

    # --- merge ---
    "By late afternoon, Dr. Kira radios in from the lab."
    hide maya_ibarra
    show dr_kira_ansel at right:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kira_ansel "We're installing the sensor mesh at Tidewatch. Data link test in twenty. If the link holds, we can stream to the town hall display."
    "You make your way back to the Tidewatch Lab, boots squeaking on wet boards. Inside, the air has that familiar smell — salt and algae and the hum of electronics. Rows of monitors glow, maps peppered"
    "with pins, and a tangle of cables that make the room look like a net of information."

    dr_kira_ansel "These sensors are ruggedized — salinity probes, pressure gauges, accelerometers on the coir rolls. They'll tell us load and erosion in near real time."
    "You trace the lines of code projected on a screen, not understanding every number but understanding the shape of it: a promise of knowledge where previously there was only guesswork."
    hide rosa_ibarra
    show maya_ibarra at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "How soon before we can read useful trends?"

    dr_kira_ansel "We get the first batch tonight. If the surge doesn't tear them out, we'll have a baseline by morning."
    hide noah_rhee
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "And if it holds, we can scale the design with real performance data rather than best guesses."
    "You exchange a look with Elliot Chen — no speeches, just two people who have spent long hours converting hope into drawings and drawings into work boots."
    # [Scene: Living Dike Pilot Site | Night — Surge Approaching]
    hide dr_kira_ansel
    hide maya_ibarra
    hide elliot_chen

    scene bg ch4_453e40_3 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Tense, then resolving into hopeful warmth]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind climbing, water thudding, the creak of stakes]
    "Rain starts as a fine grit against your cheeks. The surge comes sooner than predicted — a tide that smells of far-off swell and old stormwater. Volunteers huddle under tarps; some sleep on crates, exhausted but"
    "vigilant. You and Elliot sit on a low boardwalk, watching the sensor readouts on a tablet, numbers flicking and settling."
    "If this holds, then this thin thing of woven fiber and living root will have answered more than expectation. If it fails, we'll have more than mud to clean — we'll have to face the town's trust undone."
    "The accelerometers spike, then fall. Pressure readings climb, then level. The live feed from a camera trained on the coir roll shows waves flowing over the barrier, then receding without dragging the structure away."
    "A cheer rises from the volunteers, small and disbelieving. Someone pounds a fist on a crate. Rosa lifts her camera like a flag."
    show dr_kira_ansel at left:
        zoom 0.7

    dr_kira_ansel "Integrity holds. Minor slumping on the downstream face, but nothing catastrophic. The sensors show the anchors are doing their job."
    "You let out a breath you didn't realize you were holding. The pendant at your throat warms against your skin."
    show elliot_chen at right:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "You did this. You gathered them and made them believe enough to try."
    show maya_ibarra at center:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "We did this. You sketched, Kira measured, Noah anchored, Rosa documented. This is what I meant by holding both marsh and market."
    "Noah Rhee comes up behind you, wet hair plastered to his temple. His usual reserve has given way to practical satisfaction."
    hide dr_kira_ansel
    show noah_rhee at left:
        zoom 0.7

    noah_rhee "It held. Kids will sleep better tonight."
    "He says no more, but when he hands you a thermos of hot coffee, his fingers are rough but steady. You accept it, and the warmth flows through you like a small benediction."
    # [Scene: Tidewatch Lab / Dawn]
    hide elliot_chen
    hide maya_ibarra
    hide noah_rhee

    scene bg ch4_453e40_4 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle rising strings, bright and intimate]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soft laughter, cups clinking, gulls calling as the wind fades]
    "The morning after is small and bright. People move with that easy fatigue of accomplishment. Mayor Cortez shakes hands and promises to call the press; Tomas brings a thermos and tells an old story about a storm that once turned a whole season in one night."
    "Conversations ripple across the room. You sit with Elliot Chen at a table strewn with sensor readouts and wet gloves."
    show elliot_chen at left:
        zoom 0.7

    elliot_chen "We can show this data at the next municipal meeting. If we package it with job numbers and training programs, it's easier to sell to the council and to funders."
    show maya_ibarra at right:
        zoom 0.7

    maya_ibarra "And we'll keep the process open. No decisions without the community in the loop."

    elliot_chen "Will you still... lead if the politics get messy?"
    "You look at him, searching his face for the answer, then remember why you chose this."

    maya_ibarra "I will. But not alone."
    "His hand finds the edge of the table and, after a pause, brushes against yours. It is a small contact, ordinary and enormous."

    elliot_chen "That's all I wanted to hear."
    "Rosa appears with a new set of photos — candid frames of hands linking, eyes bright, the coir roll holding the line in a frame of broken light."
    show rosa_ibarra at center:
        zoom 0.7

    rosa_ibarra "These will make people see that it wasn't just a plan. It was a town."
    "You glance across the lab. Dr. Kira Ansel is already drafting an executive summary; Noah Rhee is showing a young fisherman how to read a tide chart. The city feels younger and older at once: younger"
    "because it has been given a new option, older because it remembers how these things often require patience."
    "This rise in morale isn't naive. It's earned. The pilot held. People saw what repair looks like. They touched the future and found it had texture — rope, reed, mud under their nails."
    "You feel the weight of the next step like the sun coming up: warm light, but also demand. There are paths ahead, each with its own price and promise. Elliot Chen looks at you the way"
    "someone offers a hand across possibilities, asking you not only where to go but how to lead."

    menu:
        "Celebrate with a small town breakfast immediately":
            "You call everyone together for a quick breakfast; laughter fills the lab; plans are swapped over coffee, and a local baker promises more bread for the next build."
        "Use the momentum to convene a technical review right away":
            "You ask Dr. Kira to prep the first report immediately; volunteers file out to rest while the technical team begins translating field notes into policy-ready language."

    # --- merge ---
    "You feel Elliot Chen's presence and the town's warmth pressing in like a tide that lifts rather than pulls away. Noah Rhee's distant gratitude hangs in the air; Dr. Kira Ansel's efficient calm hums with possibility."
    "You have done the hardest thing — to gather people and set a living thing in motion."
    "Now the question is not whether this worked. It did. The question is how you grow what just proved itself without losing the trust that made the pilot possible in the first place."
    hide elliot_chen
    hide maya_ibarra
    hide rosa_ibarra

    scene bg ch4_453e40_5 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Hopeful motif swells, then steadies]
    "You prepare to speak again, not from a podium but from the hearth of the lab, where hands and data meet."

    menu:
        "Scale quickly using community labor and decentralized funding.":
            jump chapter5
        "Request formal municipal contracts and external grants before expanding.":
            jump chapter6
        "Accept a conditional partnership with Veridian Holdings to fast-track construction while maintaining local oversight.":
